ge, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, Frankrijk","Manningford Bruce, Pewsey, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Manningford Bruce, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1425–1478":"about 1425–1478","1420–1447":"1420–1447","1442–1483":"1442–1483","–1490":"–1490","1425–1478":"1425–1478","1447":"1447","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","Abt 1425":"about 1425","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1490":"1490","Sassenage, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Sassenage, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","Allemans, Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Allemans, Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Sassenage, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Sassenage, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, France","Manningford Bruce, Pewsey, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Manningford Bruce, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alleman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Emile, Ulysse, Andre, Armande, Clovis, Colette, Desire, Monique, Ovide.","Flemish and Dutch: ethnic name from Old French <i>aleman(d)</i> ‘German’ (see also French   Allemand  , compare Dutch   Aleman  ). This surname is also found in France (Nord) and Wallonia; see also 2 below.","French (mainly Nord, Pas-de-Calais, and southern France): variant of   Allemand  . See also 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Allemann","meanings":["Swiss German: from the name of the Alemanni, an ancient Germanic tribe living in the area north of Lake Constance at the time of the Roman Empire, later used as a designation for a German living in the vicinity of the Romance speaking lands. Compare   Alleman   and   Allaman  ."]},{"name":"Allemand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Alcee, Alphonse, Andre, Raoul, Vernice.","French: from Old French <i>aleman(d)</i> ‘German’ (from Late Latin <i>Alemannus</i>, from an ancient Germanic tribal name; see   Allemann  ), hence an ethnic name for a German-speaker in a predominantly French-speaking area. Compare   Lallemand  .","Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>Alemán</b> ‘German’ (see   Aleman  , compare   Alleman   4)."]},{"name":"Aleman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Pedro, Jesus, Jorge, Miguel, Guillermo, Manuel, Julio.","Spanish (<b>Alemán</b>): from <i>alemán</i>, an ethnic name for a German, also used as a nickname for a Spanish person having some connection with Germany. Compare   Alleman   4 and   Allemand   2.","English and Dutch: ethnic name from Old French <i>aleman(d)</i> ‘German’ (compare 1 above, see also French   Allemand   and English   Allman  )."]}]},{"name":"Philippa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Philip .  In England during the Middle Ages the vernacular name <i>Philip</i> was borne by women as well as men, but female bearers were distinguished in Latin records by this form. It was not, however, used as a regular given name until the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Philippa Alleman was born about 1425, in Allemans, Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. She married Francois Berenger in 1440. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1478, in Sassenage, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, at the age of 54."},"et":{"Abt 1425–1478":"umbes 1425–1478","1420–1447":"1420–1447","1442–1483":"1442–1483","–1490":"–1490","1425–1478":"1425–1478","1447":"1447","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","Abt 1425":"umbes 1425","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1490":"1490","Sassenage, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Sassenage, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Allemans, Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Allemans, Dordogne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Sassenage, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Sassenage, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Manningford Bruce, Pewsey, Wiltshire, Eng